SOMATOTROPIN
Somatotropin, a protein of 191 amino acids, is a hormone that plays an
important role in growth control. It belongs to an evolutionarily related
family that includes choriomammotropin (lactogen), its placental analogue;
prolactin, which promotes lactation in the mammary gland, and placental
prolactin-related proteins; proliferin and proliferin related protein; and
somatolactin from various fish [1-4].

The 3D structure of bovine somatotropin has been predicted using a 
combination of heuristics and energy minimisation [5]. The model is a
four-helix bundle, in which the helices are intimately packed to form an
assembly with approximately square cross-section [5]. Adjacent helices are
anti-parallel, with a tilt between them such that the assembly has the
appearance of a left-handed twisted bundle [5]. There are two disulphide
bonds within the structure, as shown schematically below: one "hooks" the
middle of a long loop with helix 4, pulling the loop onto the surface of 
the bundle; the other "hooks" the C-terminal segment with the same helix,
forcing the C-terminus to bend towards the bundle [5]. Consequently, a 
considerable part of the bundle surface is closely packed, or intimately
embraced, by the loop segments [5]. 
                                              
